This blog is part of a blog series of Blind 75 coding problems and their solutions. Please get the list of all blind 75 problemsÂ here.
Please read the problem statement and try to solve it before reading the solution.
Approach 1
Letâ€™s say the given number isÂ n,

Find the right-most bit, if it is â€˜1â€™ countÂ it.
Right shift (bitwise) number n by 1Â bit.
Repeat step 1 and step 2 until number n is notÂ 0.

How to get the right-most bit? There are two ways to doÂ it.

Take bitwise AND (&) of n withÂ â€˜1â€™.
Divide n by 2, and the remainder will be theÂ answer.

How to right shift numberÂ n.

Use the right shift operator >> (available in most coding languages).
Divide n by 2, and the quotient will be theÂ answer.

Code for approachÂ 1.
class Solution {
public:
    int hammingWeight(uint32_t n) {
        int count = 0;
        while (n) {
            count += n % 2;
            n >>= 1;
        }
        return count;
    }
};
Time complexityÂ :Â O(1)
Space complexity: O(1)
Approach 2

Subtract one from the number n to get rid of â€˜1â€™ from n, say the number isÂ n-1.
Now, restore the remaining bits by AND operation between n andÂ n-1.
Repeat step 1 and step 2 until n is notÂ zero.
The total iteration count will be theÂ answer.

e.g. n = 1000010010

A good trick for quick implementation.
Code for approachÂ 2.
class Solution {
public:
    int hammingWeight(uint32_t n) {
        int count = 0;
        while (n) {
            count++;
            n &= n - 1;
        }
        return count;
    }
};
Time complexity: O(1)
Space complexity: O(1)
